# Technical System Flow - AI Assignment Evaluator

The following diagram illustrates the technical architecture and data flow of the application during the core evaluation process.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Student as Student (Frontend)
    participant Teacher as Teacher (Frontend)
    participant NextJS as NextJS Client
    participant Express as Express Backend
    participant Mongo as MongoDB
    participant Cloudinary as Cloudinary Storage
    participant Gemini as Google Gemini API

    %% Session Creation Flow
    rect rgb(240, 248, 255)
        Note over Teacher, Gemini: Teacher Session Creation
        Teacher->>NextJS: Creates Session (Title, Subjects, Rubric)
        Teacher->>NextJS: Uploads Question Paper & Model Answer (PDFs)
        NextJS->>Express: POST /api/faculty/create-session (multipart/form-data)
        Express->>Cloudinary: Streams files directly (Multer-Cloudinary)
        Cloudinary-->>Express: Returns Secure URLs (e.g. res.cloudinary.com/...)
        Express->>Express: Extracts fallback text via pdf-parse
        Express->>Mongo: Saves Session doc (URLs, Rubric, Settings, Teacher ID)
        Mongo-->>Express: Session ID generated
        Express-->>NextJS: Returns Session ID
        NextJS-->>Teacher: Displays Session ID for sharing
    end

    %% Student Evaluation Flow
    rect rgb(245, 255, 250)
        Note over Student, Gemini: Student Assignment Evaluation
        Student->>NextJS: Enters Name, Session ID & Uploads Assignment
        NextJS->>Express: POST /api/student/evaluate (multipart/form-data)
        Express->>Cloudinary: Streams Assignment file
        Cloudinary-->>Express: Returns Assignment URL
        Express->>Mongo: Queries Session details by ID
        Mongo-->>Express: Returns Rubric, Settings, Question URL, Model Answer URL
        Express->>Express: Extracts fallback text from Assignment

        %% The AI Pipeline
        Note right of Express: The Multi-Modal AI Pipeline
        Express->>Cloudinary: fetch() Question Paper PDF as ArrayBuffer
        Cloudinary-->>Express: Raw PDF byte buffer
        Express->>Cloudinary: fetch() Model Answer PDF as ArrayBuffer
        Cloudinary-->>Express: Raw PDF byte buffer
        Express->>Cloudinary: fetch() Student Assignment as ArrayBuffer
        Cloudinary-->>Express: Raw PDF byte buffer

        Express->>Express: Converts all 3 buffers to Base64 (inlineData)
        Express->>Gemini: POST /v1beta/models/gemini-flash:generateContent
        Note right of Gemini: Injects Strict Prompt + Rubric + Base64 PDFs
        
        Gemini-->>Express: Returns formatted JSON (Scores, Feedback, Grade)
        Express->>Express: Regex parsing & validation of JSON payload
        
        Express->>Mongo: Saves Submission doc (Student params, URL, JSON result, Session ID)
        Express-->>NextJS: Full JSON Result Payload
        NextJS-->>Student: Renders Radar Chart, Grades, & Feedback Badges
    end

    %% History Fetching Flow
    rect rgb(255, 250, 240)
        Note over Student, Mongo: History & Dashboard Retrieval
        Teacher->>NextJS: Clicks History Tab
        NextJS->>Express: GET /api/faculty/sessions (JWT Bearer)
        Express->>Mongo: find({ createdBy: teacher.id })
        Mongo-->>Express: Returns list of Sessions
        Express-->>NextJS: Renders Session List

        Teacher->>NextJS: Expands Session X
        NextJS->>Express: GET /api/student/submissions/X
        Express->>Mongo: find({ sessionId: X })
        Mongo-->>Express: Returns Submissions (with Grades/Scores)
        Express-->>NextJS: Renders Student List

        Student->>NextJS: Clicks My History
        NextJS->>Express: GET /api/student/my-submissions (JWT Bearer)
        Express->>Mongo: find({ studentId: student.id })
        Mongo-->>Express: Returns past Submissions Document List
        Express-->>NextJS: Renders historical Radar Charts
    end
```

## Key Architectural Decisions
1. **JWT & Roles:** Every request past the login boundaries includes a short-lived JSON Web Token defining the user's explicit role (`student` or `teacher`), securing the API.
2. **Cloudinary Pipeline:** Bypasses local disk I/O bottlenecks. Uploads stream directly to cloud storage, and are downloaded securely into raw memory buffers right before Gemini needs them.
3. **Multi-Modal Gemini:** By passing Base64 encoded PDF buffers into `inlineData` instead of scraped text blocks, the AI preserves the structural integrity, graphs, and formatting of the teacher's Reference materials.
4. **Regex Resiliency:** Even if Gemini hallucinates and wraps the JSON payload in markdown backticks or conversational text, [aiService.js](file:///c:/Users/abhis/Downloads/ai-evaluator/ai-evaluator/backend/aiService.js) strictly parses the data using `{[\s\S]*}` regex extractors.
